The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Broadband ramp-up by Reliance Infocomm

 ALOKANANDA GHOSH

 Calcutta, March 20: Reliance Infocomm is expanding its broadband business, especially for enterprise customers, including SMEs and major companies. The service is currently being rolled out across 30 towns and will be extended to 200 in phases.

 Deepak Verma, country head, enterprise broadband group, said, ?After expanding the mobile business, the second phase of growth will bring in the broadband revolution with links of up to 100 mbps for corporate customers. This will include a range of integrated wireline and wireless services along with value-added solutions. The aim is to become a one-stop shop for all telecom needs of the corporate customer.?

 In its nascent stage, the broadband infrastructure market is expected to take off with an estimated Rs 30,000 crore being invested by various players in laying the fibre optic backbone across the country. According to International Data Corporation, the Indian broadband equipment market is expected to touch Rs 66.52 crore this year. It is estimated that a mere 1 per cent of the available capacity is currently being used.

 Reliance Infocomm?s enterprise broadband includes services for the SMEs, SOHO and major companies. It is the SMEs and an individual entrepreneur or self-employed professional, who are expected to contribute in the broadband business growth.




